<h3 ALIGN="CENTER">RICHARD DODDRIDGE BLACKMORE</h3>

<P ALIGN="RIGHT">1825-1900

<h4><A NAME="FTN967A"></a>967&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>Dominus 
  Illuminatio Mea</i></h4>

<BLOCKQUOTE>IN the hour of death, after this life&#146;s whim,<BR>
When the heart beats low, and the eyes grow dim,<BR>
And pain has exhausted every limb&#151;<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The lover of the Lord shall trust in Him.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>When the will has forgotten the lifelong aim,<BR>
And the mind can only disgrace its fame,<BR>
And a man is uncertain of his own name&#151;<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The power of the Lord shall fill this frame.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>When the last sigh is heaved, and the last tear shed,<BR>
And the coffin is waiting beside the bed,<BR>
And the widow and child forsake the dead&#151;<BR>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The angel of the Lord shall lift this head.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <p>For even the purest delight may pall,<BR>
    And power must fail, and the pride must fall,<BR>
    And the love of the dearest friends grow small&#151;<BR>
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;But the glory of the Lord is all in all.</p>
  <p>&nbsp;</p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

